        "title": "Seeking and not seeking — the two-sided covenant posture",
        "range": "17:1-5",
        "excerpt": "The LORD was with Jehoshaphat because he followed the example of his father David's earlier days and did not seek the Baals, but sought the God of his father.",
        "body": "The chapter opens with Jehoshaphat's accession and immediate consolidation (17:1-2), but the Chronicler's real interest is established by verse 3: not what Jehoshaphat did militarily but why the LORD was with him. The evaluative formula is two-sided. Positively: he sought (*darash*) the God of his father. Negatively: he did not seek (*darash*) the Baals. The repetition of the same verb in both directions is deliberate — seeking is the governing disposition of the chapter, and it cannot be directed at two objects simultaneously.\n\nThe Chronicler's comparison to 'David's earlier days' is a calibrated theological distinction. He does not say Jehoshaphat followed David's ways simply — he specifies the *earlier* ways, the David before the Bathsheba affair, the census, and the palace politics that bloodied his later reign. This is honest historiography in service of typology: David is the model, but David is a complicated model. The Chronicler points to the part of David worth imitating. For a post-exilic community tempted to romanticize the monarchy, this is a sober word — the pattern to follow is not the full career of any human predecessor but the specific window of faithful seeking.\n\nThe result of Jehoshaphat's seeking is named plainly in verse 5: the LORD *established* (*kun*, to fix firmly, to make stable) the kingdom in his hand. The verb *kun* is the same used of God's promise to establish David's house (2 Sam. 7:12-13). The Chronicler is not writing mere court history; he is arguing that the Davidic covenant promise operates along the same mechanism in every generation — seek God, and He establishes. The tribute and honor that follow in verse 5 are not the primary goal; they are the secondary overflow of a kingdom already established by divine action.\n\nFor the Chronicler's post-exilic readers, this opening movement is the theological ground floor of their entire national project. Rebuilding the temple (Ezra 1-6), restoring the community (Nehemiah), and reestablishing the Torah (Nehemiah 8) are all acts of *darash* — seeking the God of their fathers. The chapter promises that such seeking meets a God who establishes."
