        "excerpt": "Now the dread of the LORD was on all the kingdoms of the lands which were around Judah, so that they did not make war against Jehoshaphat.",
        "body": "The peace Jehoshaphat enjoys in verses 10-11 is emphatically not the product of his garrisons, his alliances, or his diplomacy. The Chronicler is explicit: 'the dread of the LORD' (*pachad Yehovah*) fell on surrounding kingdoms. This is the theological hinge on which the chapter's security narrative turns. Jehoshaphat has placed troops (17:2) and will build fortresses (17:12) — the Chronicler does not disparage prudent preparation. But the chapter distinguishes between the human infrastructure that is appropriate stewardship and the divine action that ultimately secures the nation.\n\nThe vocabulary of *pachad* (dread, terror) connects directly to the Deuteronomic promise-structure. In Deuteronomy 2:25 and 11:25, God promises to place the dread and fear of Israel on the nations if Israel walks in His ways. The Chronicler is documenting the fulfillment of that promise in real historical time under a king who walks in God's ways, teaches God's law, and removes the competing altars. The cause-and-effect is canonical, not coincidental.\n\nThe Philistines and Arabians who bring tribute (17:11) are historically Judah's persistent border threats. Under less faithful kings they appear as raiders, invaders, and instruments of divine judgment (2 Chr. 21:16-17; 22:1). Here they appear as tributaries. The Chronicler is arguing that the same nations which become instruments of discipline when Israel is unfaithful become sources of material blessing when Israel is faithful. The nations do not change; the covenant relationship does.\n\nChuck Swindoll observes in his commentary on Chronicles that the most defensible position a community can occupy is not the one with the largest military but the one with the clearest conscience before God. 2 Chronicles 17:10 is the Chronicler's proof-text for that conviction. The chapter does not present this as a general principle — it roots it in the specific, historically-grounded covenant relationship between Yahweh and Israel."
